'''Oshitori Shrine''' (白角折神社) is a Shinto shrine located in Jōbaru, Kanzaki Town, Kanzaki City, Saga Prefecture, Japan. The site features a thousand-year-old camphor tree designated as a Saga Prefecture Natural Monument under the name "Camphor Tree of Oshitori Shrine."
== Overview and History == The shrine's origin is unclear, but it is first mentioned in the *Shinsen Shōjiroku* in the entry for the 16th day of the 9th month in the 15th year of the Jōgan era (873 CE), where the deity of Oshitori Shrine is listed as having been elevated to the rank of Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade. The shrine served as one of the guardian shrines (*chinju*) of Kanzaki Manor along with Kushida Shrine and Takashi Shrine, and was referred to as one of the "Three Shrines" (*Sansho Daimyōjin*). These three shrines are aligned along the Jōbaru River, with Oshitori Shrine located where the river transitions from the mountains to the plains.
While originally the central shrine of the three, Oshitori Shrine's prominence diminished alongside the decline of the manor system. It was officially merged with Nibiyama Shrine in 1911 (renamed to Nibiyama Shrine later that year), and its sacred object was moved there. Despite the merger, the shrine grounds and buildings were maintained by local residents, and its summer festival continues to be held.
The site contains historic relics, including a torii built in 1700 and other stone monuments bearing inscriptions.
== The Camphor Tree of Oshitori Shrine == The camphor tree (*Cinnamomum camphora*) on the shrine grounds, estimated to be over 1,000 years old, is revered as a sacred tree. Designated as a Saga Prefecture Natural Monument in 1965, it is also included in the "Saga Top 100 Notable Trees." The tree stands 22 meters tall, with a trunk circumference of 10.5 meters at chest height and a root circumference of 29.3 meters. Its unique form includes intertwined roots and large lower branches extending outward. The tree is a habitat for various epiphytes, such as ferns and small shrubs.
