[[File:Oshitori Shrine camphor tree in Kanzaki.jpg|thumb|260px|The camphor tree of Oshitori Shrine]]
'''Oshitori Shrine''' (白角折神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Kanzaki, Saga|ja|神埼市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Saga Prefecture|ja|佐賀県|12=draft}}, Japan. The precinct’s ancient camphor tree, estimated to be 1,000 years old, is designated as a {{ill|Prefectural natural monument of Japan|ja|天然記念物#都道府県指定天然記念物|12=draft}} of Saga Prefecture.

== Overview and History ==
The shrine’s exact origins are unknown. However, it appears in the {{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|三代実録|12=draft}} in the Jōgan 15 (873 CE) entry, where it is recorded as being elevated to the Rank of {{ill|Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade|ja|従五位下|1=Junior Fifth Rank|lt=Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade|12=draft}}. The shrine is also mentioned in the {{ill|Tōmyō-ji temple documents|ja|東妙寺文書|12=draft}} and the {{ill|Kushida Shrine (Saga)|ja|櫛田神社|12=draft}} documents. Together with {{ill|Kushida Shrine (Saga)|ja|櫛田宮|12=draft}} and {{ill|Takashi Shrine|ja|高志神社|12=draft}}, it formed the {{ill|Three Shrines of Kanzaki|ja|三社宮|12=draft}}, serving as the guardian shrines of {{ill|Kanzaki Manor|ja|神埼荘|12=draft}}.

The shrine is located where the {{ill|Jōbara River|ja|城原川|12=draft}} flows from the mountains to the plains, with the three shrines lined up along the river’s course. Historical records from the {{ill|Genkō era|ja|元徳元年|12=draft}} (1329) indicate that Oshitori Shrine held an influential position among the three but declined alongside the manor system’s demise.

According to records from the early {{ill|Meiji period|ja|明治時代|12=draft}}, much of the shrine’s documentation was destroyed by a fire during the {{ill|Meireki era|ja|明暦|12=draft}} or washed away in a flood in 1866. Surviving sources suggest it once housed documents connected to the {{ill|Ashikaga clan|ja|足利氏|12=draft}} and {{ill|Shōni clan|ja|少弐氏|12=draft}}. The 1866 flood also destroyed the shrine buildings, which were later rebuilt.

In 1911, Oshitori Shrine was merged into Nihiyama Shrine, with its deity relocated there. However, the precincts and shrine structures were preserved by the local community, and its summer festival continues to this day. Historically, the shrine hosted {{ill|Kagura|ja|神楽|12=draft}} performances. The main shrine holds two ancient wooden statues: one of a goddess dated to {{ill|Jōwa era|ja|貞和|12=draft}} 2 (1346) and one of a male deity carved from a single paulownia trunk.

== The Camphor Tree of Oshitori Shrine ==
The camphor tree in the shrine precincts, revered as a {{ill|Sacred tree|ja|神木|12=draft}}, is estimated to be 1,000 years old. It was designated a natural monument of Saga Prefecture in 1965 and later included in the "Saga 100 Famous Trees" list. The tree measures 22 meters in height, with a trunk circumference of 10.5 meters at chest height and a root spread of 29.3 meters. Despite minor hollowing, it remains vigorous, with extensive branching and a crown that spreads 32 meters east-west and 26 meters north-south. Various epiphytic plants such as {{ill|Microsorum|ja|ノキシノブ|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ligustrum|ja|ネズミモチ|12=draft}}, and ferns grow on its surface.

